    <h1> Creative Commons</h1>
	<p> Creative Commons (CC) is an international nonprofit organization that empowers people to grow and sustain
	    the thriving commons of shared knowledge and culture we need to address the worldâ€™s most pressing challenges 
	    and create a brighter future for all.  Creative Commons strives to provide equitably  shared education
		culture, and science to benefit humanity.  They  empowers individuals and communities around the world through 
		technical, legal, and policy solutions that enable the sharing of education, culture, and science in the public interest.
		There tools remove friction and barriers in sharing and accessing knowledge.
		They Provide CC licenses and public domain tools that give every person and organization in the world a free, simple, 
		and standardized way to grant copyright permissions for creative and academic works; ensure proper attribution; 
		and enable others to copy, distribute, and make use of those works.</p>
		
		<!--List of different Creative Commons-->
      <ul> Six different types of Creative Commons Licenses!
	    <li><strong> CC BY:</strong> This allows reusers to distribute, remix, adapt, and build
		 upon the material in any type of medium or format.  The user has togive credit 
		 to the creator.  Ex: BY:credit to creator</li>
		 
		 <li><strong> CC BY-SA:</strong> This allows reusers to the same as CC BY except if you 
		 modify the material you have to give crdit to to creator and adaptations must be shared
         the same terms.  Ex: BY: credit must be given to the creator and.
         SA: Adaptations must be shared under the same terms.	 
		 
		 <li><strong> CC BY-NC:</strong> This license provides all the abilitues of the CC By,
		  but it is used for noncommercial purposes only and as long as the creator 
		  is given credit. BY: credit must be given to the creator.
          NC: Only noncommercial uses of the work are permitted. Ex:</li>
		  
		  <li><strong>CC BY-NC-SA:</strong>This license allows the reusers to distribute 
		   remix, adapt, and build upon for noncommercial purposes only.  Credit must be given to creator, there 
		   must be acknowledgement of adaption, and it must be noncommercial.
		   Ex:BY: credit must be given to the creator.
           NC: Only noncommercial uses of the work are permitted.
           SA: Adaptations must be shared under the same terms.</li>
		   
		   <li><strong>CC BY-ND</strong>This license allowes reusers to copy and distribute the
		    material or format in unadapated form only, the creator must be given credit.  This license can be used 
			for commerical use.  EX: BY: credit must be given to the creator.
            ND: No derivatives or adaptations of the work are permitted. </li>
			
			<li><strong>CC BY-NC-ND:</strong>This license allows reusers to copy and distribute the material in any 
			medium or format in unadapted form only, for noncommercial purposes only.  Credit must be given to the creator 
			and other attributes.  Ex:BY: credit must be given to the creator.
            NC: Only noncommercial uses of the work are permitted.
            ND: No derivatives or adaptations of the work are permitted.</li>
	  </ul>	

      <1--3 Different typs of Copyright Materials-->
	  <h2><em>3 Different Types of Copyright Material</em></h2>
	  <p> There are three different types of copyright material which refers to how copyright material can be used.
	   Public domain, Fair use act, and License content gives three different ways to obtain material from a creator.  
        Listed below are the the different ways they are used to be able to share peoples work.	   </p>
	  
	  <p><strong>Public domain</strong> allows authors to keep and manage their copyright on terms they choose.
        It enable authors and copyright owners who want to dedicate their works to the worldwide public domain to do so, 
		and facilitate the labeling and discovery of works that are already free of known copyright restrictions.	
		
		<strong>Fair Use</srong>gives users the right to use copyrighted material without permission under 
		 certain circumstances.  Some purposes are: criticism, comment, news reporting, teaching, scholarship, or research.
		 
		 <strong>License Content</strong>is an agreement between the creator and the website owner for the use of the material.
		  It would outline the terms and conditions of the material that will be used. 
		  The agreement would include items such as: Payment, duration, scope of use, restriction, and attributions.</p>
		  
		  
